  {# ── Overview ── #}
  <h2 id="overview" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600 vf-search-client-side--no-index">Overview</h2>

  <p>Images and media content often represent the largest portion of a webpage's total file size. Optimising images and videos is therefore one of the most effective ways to improve website performance, especially for users on slow networks or limited devices.</p>

  <p>In low-resource environments such as LMIC regions, large media files can dramatically increase loading time, data usage, and rendering delays. A well-designed image and media strategy ensures that visual content remains useful and engaging without negatively affecting performance or accessibility.</p>

  <p>The goal of an LRO-friendly media strategy is to deliver the smallest possible media files that still communicate the intended visual information, while ensuring that images and videos load progressively and only when needed.</p>

  {# ── Why this matters for LRO ── #}
  <h2 id="why-lro" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Why this matters for LRO</h2>

  <p>Large images and videos can slow down websites significantly and consume large amounts of bandwidth. This problem becomes much more pronounced in low-resource environments, where users often rely on slow mobile networks or have strict data limits.</p>

  <p>Optimised images help achieve several important outcomes:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Faster page loading and improved user experience</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Reduced data consumption for users</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Better performance on low-power devices</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Improved search engine performance and Core Web Vitals scores</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Research shows that when page load time increases from one second to three seconds, the bounce rate can increase significantly, meaning many users leave before the page finishes loading.</p>

  <p>Because images are frequently the largest element on a webpage, they often determine the Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) metric used in performance evaluation.</p>

  {# ── Common Problems ── #}
  <h2 id="common-problems" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Common Problems</h2>

  <p>Many websites unintentionally degrade performance because of inefficient media usage. Typical problems include:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Large uncompressed images uploaded directly from cameras</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Images much larger than the size displayed on screen</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Use of heavy formats such as PNG when JPEG or WebP would be smaller</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Video backgrounds that load immediately on page load</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Multiple decorative images that do not add meaningful content</li>
  </ul>

  <p>These issues can significantly increase page size and delay rendering.</p>

  <p>Another common issue is using the same image for all devices. Serving a large desktop image to a mobile device wastes bandwidth and increases loading time.</p>

  {# ── Design Principles ── #}
  <h2 id="design-principles" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Design Principles</h2>

  <p>A sustainable media strategy for low-resource environments follows several key principles:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Use images only when they provide real value to the content</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Serve the right image size for each device</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Deliver media progressively rather than loading everything at once</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Optimise file size without sacrificing necessary quality</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Prefer formats that offer better compression</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Reducing the number of images and serving device-appropriate images can significantly reduce bandwidth usage and improve performance.</p>

  {# ── Implementation Guidance ── #}
  <h2 id="implementation" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Implementation Guidance</h2>

  <h3>Image Formats and When to Use Them</h3>

  <p>Different image formats are suitable for different types of content.</p>

  <h4>JPEG</h4>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Best for photographs and detailed images.</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Uses lossy compression to reduce file size.</li>
  </ul>

	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
