  <h3>General Guidance</h3>

  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Use WebP or AVIF for most images</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Use SVG for icons and diagrams</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Use JPEG only when compatibility is required</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Avoid PNG for large images</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Image Sizing and Resolution</h3>

  <p>Image resolution is often misunderstood in web optimisation. DPI values are primarily relevant for print and do not significantly affect how images appear on screens. What matters more is the actual pixel dimensions of the image.</p>

  <p>Best practices for image sizing include:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Resize images to match their display size</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Avoid uploading images larger than needed</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Typical web images should be around 1000px wide</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Logos and icons should be much smaller</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Oversized images increase page weight without improving visual quality.</p>

  <h3>Responsive Images</h3>

  <p>Different devices require different image sizes. Responsive images ensure the browser downloads only the most appropriate version.</p>

	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
		<img src="{{ '/images/content_images/LRO diagram 3.2.5d.avif' | url }}" alt="Use lazy loading for assets that are not required during the initial page render." loading="lazy">
		<figcaption class="vf-figure__caption"></figcaption>
	</figure>

  <p><strong>Example using the &lt;picture&gt; element:</strong></p>
  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;picture&gt;
  &lt;source
    media="(max-width:700px)"
    srcset="hero-mobile-400.jpg 400w,
            hero-mobile-700.jpg 700w"&gt;
  &lt;source
    media="(min-width:701px)"
    srcset="hero-desktop-700.jpg 700w,
            hero-desktop-1200.jpg 1200w"&gt;
  &lt;img src="hero-desktop-1200.jpg"
       alt="Scientific dataset visualisation"&gt;
&lt;/picture&gt;</code></pre>

  <p>This approach ensures that smaller devices download smaller images, saving bandwidth and improving loading speed.</p>

  <h3>Lazy Loading</h3>

  <p>Lazy loading delays the loading of images until they are needed, typically when they appear in the viewport.</p>

  <p><strong>Benefits include:</strong></p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Faster initial page load</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Reduced network requests</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Lower data usage</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;img src="dataset-image.jpg" loading="lazy" alt="Dataset illustration"&gt;</code></pre>

  <p>Lazy loading is especially important for long pages containing many images.</p>

